 Looking at the architecture, there are more robust approaches than the unregister/re-register dance. Here are the alternatives, from most practical to most invasive:

## Option 1: Wrap `modelRegistry.getApiKeyAndHeaders` (Recommended)

This is where headers are resolved before each request. You could patch this at the extension level:

```typescript
pi.on("session_start", async (_event, ctx) => {
  const modelRegistry = ctx.modelRegistry;

  // Store original
  const originalGetAuth = modelRegistry.getApiKeyAndHeaders.bind(modelRegistry);

  // Wrap to inject headers
  modelRegistry.getApiKeyAndHeaders = async (model) => {
    const result = await originalGetAuth(model);
    if (!result.ok) return result;

    return {
      ...result,
      headers: {
        ...result.headers,
        "User-Agent": `kimchi/${getVersion()}`,
        // Add any other runtime headers
      }
    };
  };
});
```

**Pros:** Headers injected at the source, works for all providers, survives model switches  
**Cons:** Patching internal methods is still somewhat fragile

## Option 2: Use `registerApiProvider` from `@mariozechner/pi-ai`

Register a wrapper at the API level that intercepts all `openai-completions` calls:

```typescript
import { registerApiProvider, getApiProvider } from "@mariozechner/pi-ai";

const originalProvider = getApiProvider("openai-completions");

registerApiProvider({
  api: "openai-completions",
  stream: (model, context, options) => {
    // Inspect/modify headers here
    console.log("Outgoing headers:", options?.headers);
    return originalProvider!.stream(model, context, options);
  },
  streamSimple: (model, context, options) => {
    return originalProvider!.streamSimple(model, context, {
      ...options,
      headers: {
        ...options?.headers,
        "User-Agent": `kimchi/${getVersion()}`,
      }
    });
  }
}, "kimchi-header-injector");
```

**Pros:** Clean API-level interception, official extension point  
**Cons:** Must be done early (before first request), affects all providers using that API type

## Option 3: Model-level header injection

The `Model` objects have a `headers` property that's checked on each request. You could modify models at runtime:

```typescript
pi.on("model_select", async (event) => {
  const model = event.model;
  if (model) {
    model.headers = {
      ...model.headers,
      "User-Agent": `kimchi/${getVersion()}`,
    };
  }
});
```

**Pros:** Simple, uses public API  
**Cons:** Headers may be merged/overridden by provider-level headers later in the chain

